The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, January 28, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 State Bank of India has entered into an alliance with HDFC Bank for sharing ATM networks to be effective from February 3. As a result, customers of State Bank and its seven associates would have access to 870 ATMs of HDFC Bank, while customers of the private sector bank would be able to use State Banks 2,850 ATMs. The users would be able to withdraw cash and make balance enquiry, a State Bank release said.																								 Close on the heels of opening an outlet in the Philippines, leading jewellery maker Tanishq said it expected a jump of 200-300 per cent in sales from its campaign of get gold free with diamonds. Unveiling the campaign, Tanishq head (marketing) Y. L. Saroja said, There was always a rise in sales during any promotional campaign.																								 Indian Oil Corporation (IOC) has signed a memorandum of understanding with Coffee Day Xpress for setting up coffee bars and take-away kiosks at its retail outlets and is to shortly sign a pact with Foodworld for convenience stores in select markets. 																								 National Hydroelectric Power Corporation (NHPC) has awarded a Rs 2,000-crore civil works contract to Larsen amp; Toubro and a Russian consortium for 2000 MW lower Subanshiri project.																								 Pragati Growth amp; Development, an innovative infrastructure solution provider, has collaborated with West Bengal Industrial Development Corporation (WBIDC) to form Bengal Pragati Infrastructure Development Ltd for conceptualising and implementing infrastructure development projects in Bengal.																								 ITC has signed a memorandum of understanding with the Andhra Pradesh government to develop wastelands in the state under the Velugu programme. ITC and the state government will synergise their strengths in forestry development in the Khammam district of Andhra Pradesh.																								 Gujarat NRE Coke is increasing its capacity by setting up a greenfield project for the manufacture of lam coke at Kandia in Gujarat. This project will help the company more than double its production capacity from 3.97 lakh metric tonne per annum to 7.21 lakh metric tonne per annum.																								 Haldia-based Hind Lever Chemicals Ltd (HLCL) has won the Fertiliser Association of Indias best performance award for its phosphoric acid plant. In 2001 and 2002, HLCL had received this award for its single superphosphate plant.																								 LG Electronics India Ltd has started a service camp for its products from January 27. It will last till February 3. During this period anybody owning an LG product can call up the toll-free number 9622990990 and lodge a complaint. ADVERTISEMENT
